<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF108-310-550  </DOCNO><DOCID>08 310 550.andM;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Digital Review  April 2 1990 v7 n13 p21(1)* Full Text COPYRIGHT Ziff-Davis Publishing Co. 1990.andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Project management package tracks MIS resources. (managementinformation system; Cincom's Comprehensive Planning and ControlSystem) (product announcement)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Patch, Kimberly.andM;</AUTHOR><SUMMARY>Cincom Systems Inc introduces the Comprehensive Planning andControl System (CPCS), an accounting software package for IBM andDEC systems that is designed for information systems departments.andO;The product can support various departments, many informationsystems resources, activities and projects simultaneously, lettingusers know when projects divert from original plans.andP;  The CPCSenables users to create cost-accounting and budgeting models forinformation systems activities, projecting future budgets andkeeping track of expenditures.andP;  A project management component ofthe package includes proprietary graphic capabilities to draw Pertor knowledge-based, cost-trend analysis charts.andP;  CPCS is pricedfrom $24,700 to $119,900 depending on hardware configuration andmodules involved.andM;</SUMMARY><DESCRIPT>Company:   Cincom Systems Inc. (product introduction).andO;Product:   Comprehensive Planning and Control System (Data center managementsoftware) (product introduction).andO;Topic:     Product IntroductionProject Management SystemsAccounting.andM;</DESCRIPT><TEXT>Project management package tracks MIS resourcesandM;CINCINNATI--Cincom has released an accounting software package for DEC andIBM systems that is designed for information systems departments.andM;The Comprehensive Planning and Control System (CPCS) can support manyinformation systems resources, departments, activities and projectssimultaneously, and can keep track of how these projects divert from originalplans, according to Cincom Project Manager Dan Riehle.andM;The CPCS program allows users to create budgeting and cost-accounting modelsfor information systems activities.andP;  The models can be used to project futurebudgets and keep track of expenditures.andM;&quot;It supports your planning but expects [and] supports changes, and reports[possible] changes ahead of time [as] an impact analysis.&quot;andP;  Riehle said.andM;The software also allows users to simulate the effects of possible changes ina project.andM;&quot;On a typical day [information systems employees] might do something totallydifferent from what they planned.andP;  When you get finished with that day, youwant to know what your resources spent their time on.andP;  If you had to pullthem off [a planned task], you might have to report [that],&quot; he said.andM;With the CPCS software, &quot;not only can you report to a project manager ...andO;what some changes cost, but you can report to the rest of the company&quot; howthose changes are going to affect it, he said.andM;The program also includes a skills inventory system where skill sets aredefined for both information systems personnel and information systems tasks.andO;The program will then match tasks to personnel.andM;A project management component includes proprietary graphics capabilitiesthat can be used to produce Pert of knowledge-based, cost-trend analysischarts.andM;A documentation and report writer is also available as an integrated part ofthe package.andM;The software runs on VAXes under VMS and in IBM CICS environments.andM;CPCS is available now, priced from $24,700 to $119,900, depending on themodules needed and the hardware configuration.andM;Cincom Systems Inc. is located at 2300 Montana Ave., Cincinnati, OH45211-3899, (513) 661-6000.andO;</TEXT></DOC>